column73: Feedback
I would answer the same to all of these questions that still made sense if it was 'a person' rather than 'a man'.
Should question four read "A man doesn't let..."
None
i feel a huge chunk of these would have benefited from a "better if applied equally to both genders" button

I think the issue with holding up specific standards as positive, is that historically they've been used to suggest that any other behaviour is substandard. They create a place where sexism and similar can grow.

Many of these things would be useful or not depending heavily on context - hence the many 'neutral' responses. So something like 'When appropriate, a man should -', rather than 'At all times, regardless of external factors, a man should -'.
I'm not quite sure how to answer when I see a positive trait, but the masculinity/femininity of the person with this trait is not germane to the value of it
The Question "A man accepts survival of the fittest and does not let his neighbor's failures taint his success" appears, to me at least, to deal with two entirely separate concepts.

I felt most of the questions would apply to all genders, except the ones I consider sexist or bias towards women. I think regardless of my personal preferences over what an ideal manly man is, my feeling is that all men are valid even if they don't fit these criteria. I tried to pick out some positive attributes that I would find would be specific to men, but it was very hard to separate these attributes from things I find positive about, well, everyone.
Consider including options for 'undesirable' and 'very undesirable' (I understand that you have one of these already)

The question on the penis; it was unclear if "undesirable" was about the requirement, or the presence. I answered as though it was the presence (neutral - I don't think it needs to be there, and it is not a definitive indicator) but I wasn't sure if that was the way you intended it to be.
I answered neutral to everything, as none of these qualities are essential to 'being a man', though they may be perceived as masculine.

1. Thank you for doing this.
2. As has been said elsewhere, neutral vs. irrelevant is something I had issues with. Things that are neither undesirable nor undesirable about a person, but nothing to do with being a man is something that it would be better to resolve. My approach was to put these into neutral.
What box do
Mainly neutral as didn't define a man.

Probably better to put "sex" rather than "gender" in the first question: people are treated differently based on their sex and gender tends to be used to justify it. I put "woman" because I'm female but I don't identify with any gender because I don't believe they are real.
Maybe make the spectrum around 'agree to disagree' as opposed to the current "desirable to undesirable" as answers can be less ambiguous.
To simplistic

column3: Liberal, Men's Rights Activist, Egalitarian, Moderate
column73: Many of the statements in this survey would have the same response if they began "A person" rather than "A man" in order to get more accurate results you may want to have all the questions with "A woman" infront in order to tease out those traits which are desirable only or especially of men.
Some questions were quite ambiguous and not always the answer I gave was an answer I could swear on as valid in 100% of cases :/

column3: Socialist, Liberal, Conservative, Libertarian, Anarchist, Feminist, Men's Rights Activist, Egalitarian, Moderate

column73:
A lot of these questions are best answered with one or more of:

* "X is a laudable quality, but ..." and "women should be able to do that too" or "it is not required to do this to be a man" or both.
* "People are individuals, some people like this, others don't".
* "The world would be a better place if women also did this, not just men".

Some that I want to give more specific answers to:

> A man eats whatever food he wants.

A man should not be prevented from eating something just because he is a man. OTOH, factors such as availability, cost, health, etc, may suggest that *people* (not just men, all people) may not be able to eat "whatever they want". A few less land-whales (of either gender) would do society some good.

> A man is unashamed of his sexual desires.

People have individuals. Some people have wrong desires, and there may be cause to be ashamed of them. But normal male sexual desire absolutely should not be the subject of shaming, which it currently is.

> A man does not make demands of his friends.

People making demands (note the language -- demands, not requests...) of their friends aren't nice friends.

> A man prioritises clarity and directness over politeness and people-pleasing.

While a level of politeness is good, honesty is also good. The world would likely be a less confusing place if *all people* did this. This is an area where women are more in need of change TBH.

> A man makes the first move, sexually and romantically.

"People are individuals". Some people want to sit back and see what comes up. Others want to be proactive and see what they can get. The issue here is when a man tries the former, *nothing happens*. Women simply do not approach men. This is something they need to start doing. Add the forces of hypergamy, and we're going to get a whole generation of very well looked after cats, and a plummeting birth rate, unless something changes.

> A man does not speak ill of others.

I would be happy to agree with this if the word 'unjustly' is added. Sometimes people need ill to be spoken of them, because they need to learn what they are doing wrong. And when they don't learn, others need to be told in order to cull their following and make them less dangerous. This is irrespective of gender.

> A man does not trouble others with his feelings until he has made sense of them himself.

Men typically heal differently. Shoulder to shoulder, rather than face to face. We as a society need to recognise this. The Mens Shed movement taps into this -- if feminists could please stop shooting it down wherever it appears, that would be nice...

> A man keeps his feelings to himself.

While this is a typical male trait anyway, it would be nice to move away from it a little. The key here is when a man does share his feelings ... he gets shamed for it. Mostly by women, and *particularly* by feminists. Consequently, this is likely unobtainable, because convincing either group they are wrong and need to change for the benefit of men is about as likely as winning the lotto every single week for a year. But it sure would be nice...

> A man does what he says he will do, and does not make promises he cannot keep.

This needs to apply to all people. Not just men. It's not men that are failing at this one, by and large...

> A man is ready to use physical force or violence where it is necessary.

This comes down to the definitions of "force", "violence" and "necessary".

It's necessary to use physical force to shift a crashed car that's trapping an injured person, for example. I mean, do you want them to bleed out, and no-one to do anything? But I bet you any money that's not what you wanted this question to mean...

> A man does not rely on the kindness of others.

Relying on others is not good. Accepting it when given is OK, and needing it occasionally when things go wrong is OK, but continued reliance on others is not.

> A man is able to provide financially for himself and others.

It would be nice if we could move away from 'man as provider for family' to 'people look after themselves, everyone is independent' -- but hypergamy is a thing, so unless we manage to break that (and that's biologically influenced, so that will take millennia, not decades), this is here to stay. Given hypergamy existing, the alternative is state reliance, which is not good.

> A man will defend his integrity if it is questioned.

Anyone should be able to defend themselves when (verbally) attacked, which is what this implies.

> A man puts the lives of others over himself.

Necessary for some subset of the population (otherwise you wouldn't have firefighters, for example), but shouldn't be required as a universal.

> A man puts the needs and feelings of others before himself.

Yeah, no. Someone has to care for the man. It used to be that a man put the needs of his family first, and in return, they looked after him. The latter has broken, so we either need to repair it, or the former needs to be broken too before men, as a whole, crash and burn.

> A man does not lie.

White lies are sometimes necessary, particularly with women. The correct answer to "does my arse look fat in this" is never "yes", even if it's true. But broadly speaking, people (all people, not just men) should avoid spreading significant lies.

> A man is quick to form an opinion, and quick to defend it.

Quick should be removed from this.

Anyone should be free to form an opinion, and should be capable of defending it. Everyone should also be open to rational debate and questioning, and be willing to be persuaded of a different position.

> A man's worth is measured by his accomplishments.

This is currently objectively true. Women are recognised as valuable to society just for having reaching childbearing age without dying. Men are not. Men are worth their last good act, and no more.

We need to reach a point somewhere in the middle for both. Human males are unique amongst all living organisms in their ability to co-operate outside of related family groups. This ability should be celebrated, as it is critical to society. OTOH, women need to be judged more on their actions, the power of the "woman card" needs to come down several notches.

> A man does not need to prove himself to others.

Eh, I think this is never going to go away. But if we could both widen it (to all people, not just men) and soften it (so we are more tolerant of failures), that would be good.

> A man speaks his mind.

Men used to speak their minds. Now, they get shamed for it. We as a society need to stop this. People speaking their minds is essential to the open marketplace of ideas, and only from there will we find the best ideas to go forward.

> A man knows everything about something, and something about everything.

The ideal T shaped person. A wide breadth of knowledge, and a deep knowledge of one specialist subject.

Holding this up as an ideal for ALL people (yes, women too) is broadly a good thing. Expecting people meet it, or declaring them an unperson for failing to, is not.

> A man does not let his feelings cloud his judgement.

Judgement clouded by feelings is also called "women's ways of knowing". It would be great if we could get away from that. For both genders...

> A man seeks advice when he wants to find a solution.

The key here is to make it socially acceptable for one man to mentor another man without shaming. As a society, we used to do this. Now we do not.

> A man channels his anger and frustrations to productive ends.

It's not necessary for a person to have anger and frustrations. But if they do, channelling it to productive ends is the best use for it. This should apply to both genders.

> A man is financially independent.

Independent of what? The state? Ideally yes, everyone should be financially independent of the state. On average though, it's not men who have this problem. The average man is a net contributor to the state eventually (taking benefits, typically in the form of education as a child and young adult), and paying that back in tax by middle age, then becoming a net contributor before retirement. The average woman is the opposite -- they do not pay enough tax to cover the initial start-up cost to the state of their education and early life during their working life, and then provide a heavier retirement burden after retiring.

If you mean "independent of women" ... then, that's a matter for each individual family. The problem keeping this expectation current is the high rate of relationship failure when a woman out-earns a man. Look at relationships where a man stops working to look after the kids -- hypergamy kicks in, and the woman kicks up a stink and breaks the relationship up -- even though she instigated the arrangement in the first place.

Now think of this in terms of what feminists call "the wage gap" (and is more accurately called "the earnings gap"). If we ever closed it completely, we'd destroy the institution of marriage. And interestingly, the earnings gap for people who have never married is in favour of women.

> A man cultivates as many interests as is possible.

People are individuals. A man should have interests - but whether he chooses to immerse himself deeply in just one interest or has a number of shallow interests is up to him and his personality. This applies equally to all genders.

> A man is secure in his convictions, and is not easily swayed by the words of others.

A man should listen to evidence. If his convictions are wrong, being persuaded by persuasive evidence is not a bad quality. But keeping quiet or toeing the line because of public shaming is bad. More confidence to speak out against obvious bullshit is something we've lost, and is necessary to re-gain.

> A man powers through a problem when grace or finesse fails.

Occasionally necessary in order to get something done. Without this quality, it's likely civilisation as we know it would simply not exist.

> A man is quick to respond in a time of crisis.

Speed is not necessarily the appropriate cause of action. Consideration and awareness is also required. Rushing in is sometimes necessary, but can sometimes also be bad.

> A man cherishes and values the qualities of women.

... where those qualities are positive. Where they are negative and they need to change, he should be willing to call them out.

> A man is faithful to his roots.

Steadfastly sticking to tradition for tradition's sake is wrong. But looking carefully and seeing the *reason* for it, then sticking with it because you know why it's done that way, that I support.

> A man is willing and able to please his sexual partners.

Two way street here. This is not just one person's job. After all, it's not men who typically 'go starfish', is it...

> A man does not perceive something as a threat to him unless it is a real danger.

A laudable quality that men still mostly have, although certain "progressives" are starting to lack it. Please can we extend this to everyone, regardless of gender. Please.

> A man may take a beating, of whatever kind, but he gets back up afterwards.

If we could stop expecting men to take beatings, that'd be nice. Nevertheless, it's an admirable quality to be able to fall (whether physically or metaphorically), and get back up afterwards.

> A man takes the lead in bed.

People are individuals. Some people like to lead. Some people like to follow. Provided everyone involved is happy, can we please just leave them to it?

> A man puts his bonds with other men first.

This is a total misunderstanding of 'bros before hoes'. What this actually means is valuing long term friendship over short term relationships. That is entirely valid and laudable. Gender is immaterial to it.

> A man has the confidence to speak authoritatively, unless he is proven wrong.

Anyone with the evidence to back up what they are saying should be able to speak authoritatively.

> A man helps other men to be good men.

Oh boy, this could go SO many ways.

We definitely need to bring back mentorship, which would fit this statement to a tee.

But the "pledge to end violence against women" thing (when two thirds of women go through an entire lifetime without seeing violence ever, not even once, yet all men will have experienced it repeatedly before they've finished growing up) is a horrid, horrid twisting of this statement.

On that last one, the key thing is to teach women not to hit men. We currently instil in them a sense of absolute safety - you can hit him and he can't defend himself. This is awful for society. I would prefer to teach everyone not to hit anyone, but failing that, making self defense when assaulted an acceptable act for a man is a reasonable compromise.

> A man arrives to occasions on time.

Timeliness is an admirable quality. Some people just don't have it. This is not tied in any way to masculinity.

> A man has the confidence that if something is broken, it can be fixed.

The ability to fix things is an admirable quality. Being a man is irrelevant.

> A man has a penis.

One one level, that's kinda the point. Men have penises, women have vaginas. That's how language works. I can't just call my cat a dog and expect everyone else to go along with this.

On another level, I'm sure what you're trying to measure here is either related to intersex conditions or transgender issues.

Intersex is a (range of...) real medical conditions. Gender dysphoria is a real medical condition. All are rare (we're talking fractions of a percent here). Both are reasonable and can result in someone who presents male but might not have a penis, or vice-versa. Ultimately (unless you are looking for a relationship) this fact is entirely irrelevant.

A trend that does need to go away is tumblrisms though. There are two genders. They are heavily biologically influenced. Tomboys are still girls -- they just have some stereotypically male interests. They aren't trans kids. The reverse is also fine. Liking 'My little pony' doesn't make you female for 15 minutes at a time while the show is on.

Incidentally, the very existence of gender dysphoria absolutely and conclusively disproves gender being a social construct. Gender Dysphoria would not even be possible if gender did not have a strong biological component.

> A man uses his wealth and social standing for the benefit of others.

Society benefits when this happens, and philanthropy is a laudable quality. But this isn't a requirement of being a man. Philanthropy should be available to women, too, and the vast majority of men aren't wealthy and don't have social standing -- yet they are still men.

> A man is willing to endure suffering gladly in order to accomplish his goals.

Choosing to endure suffering in order to achieve something is laudable -- but not inherently tied to being male.

> A man does man's work, and lets women do women's work.

What is meant here by "mans work" and "womens work"? People are individuals, and while statistically there are differences, there will always be individuals that don't fit the stereotype.

Being able to work is laudable. Choosing to do something you are good at is beneficial. Enjoying work is the proverbial icing on the cake.

And evolution has made certain things easier for certain genders. But that doesn't mean there aren't exceptions.

I learned this at the age of 12 on a factory tour. The big, heavy, dirty machinery was 100% male operated. One section was mass producing a very fiddly set of small components. Most (but not all) of the operators of this machinery were female. It did not require strength to operate. Instead it depended on repeated accurate placement of lots of small fiddly components.
For so many of those, it seemed desirable for a *person* to do that thing, but it only seemed appropriate for a man to do them *because* they were a person, so I selected neutral.

Some questions can be taken very differently, and could have varying answers. Also, I don't think my answers would have been very different with "a woman" instead, although, of course, there is a difference between what we think and how we act :-(

column3: Liberal, Libertarian, Anarchist, Men's Rights Activist, Egalitarian
column73: Thank you for doing this survey. Not only was it great to help the cause, but it's interesting to see ideas of manhood laid out like this; although I'm interested in men's issues, there are many things on this list that I'd have never considered to be part of the "man box." Great work!

I could not answer these questions because this still asserts a philosophy of difference. A person should do X. This is the standard by which men, women, and all genders must operate. A person should be seen as complex and permitted a wide range of social behaviors, as long as those do not infringe unduly and aggressively on others.

column73: There is no such thing as 'toxic' masculinity
I know the point of this was what men should strive to be, but I kind of answered it as what any and all humans should strive towards.

column3: Socialist, Liberal, Libertarian, Feminist, Egalitarian, Moderate

column73: All of these behaviours and responses are less what I feel a man should be like specifically but more what should apply to people in general regardless of sex or gender.

Many of these questions were difficult to answer and I must admit that, for a few of them, I had to supplement "person" for man I'm afraid. (As the question didn't make sense to me as a gendered question). Sorry if that skews your results, and if you'd like to remove these answers from the study I won't be offended! 😁

column3: Socialist, Liberal, Libertarian, Feminist, Egalitarian, Moderate
column73: Most of my responses I believe should apply to both genders.

You have options to select various genders - awesome! But all the questions are couched in terms of men or women - there's no other mention of other gender identities, and this kinda reinforces binary thinking. You could just replace 'women' with 'other genders' and solve this easily.

It is difficult to think with out the social conditioning I have been brought up with. Generally the traits I have identified as desirable or essential are qualities that I would apply to either gender, including the opening doors for others question as that is just good manners towards others.

I deny the concept of masculinity as a sound normative concept. It was only the qualification that "women may pursue and attain these values" which convinced me to complete the form at all. In all instances, therefore, I have answered with a view to reading "A man..." as "A person...". This may, I realise render my answers useless. Hopefully you can filter them accordingly if that is the case.
Some interestingly worded, interesting questions. Much food for thought.

column3: Socialist, Liberal, Anarchist, Feminist, Egalitarian, Moderate
column73: For pretty much every answer, substitute "men" with "people" and my answers would not change.
I'd like to know how people respond to these questions when they are asked about women.

column3: Socialist, Libertarian, Feminist, Men's Rights Activist, Egalitarian, Moderate
column73: Were even 5% of those questions even relative to masculinity?

Eventually with these questions I just went neutral; a man should not 'be' anything. A man is simply a person who identifies so. Nothing else should surround that. They are not cornerstones of anything, they are not the foundations of what is right. They are not people onto which the pressure to be unyielding or perfect should be placed. They are who they are, and I do not wish to strongly a line the idea of a 'man', knowing all men are different, to any statement other than 'they are human, and should be free to feel the way they do, safely and with courtesy to those around them', like anyone.
Answered these as "What I would like The man of 2017 to be" and am very aware that these are different to "How I, a man of 2017, think and act"

column3: Socialist, Liberal, Libertarian, Feminist, Egalitarian, Moderate

column73:
Would change the wording of absolute terms.

"Essential" implies that something absolutely must be true. This can only truly be said to apply to one question "A man uses violence where necessary", on the basis that "necessary" implies in this instance that use of violence is arbitrarily essential. 

I know that by essential, you mean to say that the behaviour should be core to who the man is, but it's still unclear to me what the remit of "core behaviour" really is, and when a behaviour is more than just desirable, or even important. Nevertheless, I have filled this questionnaire with the assumption that "Essential" means "Highly Desirable or Essential", but I have not assumed anything about the word "necessary".

I answered a lot of questions with "Neutral", but this does not reflect my feelings for many of these questions.

In some questions, like "A man does not perceive something to be a threat unless it is a real danger", I answered "Neutral", because the only way it would be possible for a man to fulfil this statement absolutely would be through clairvoyance; a trait humans are not known to possess. 

Other questions, such as "A man's worth is measured through his accomplishments", are vague. It is unclear whether it is desirable (for example) for the man to measure his own worth through his accomplishments, or for other men to value his worth through his accomplishments. I believe my answers to these questions would probably be different to one another.

For me most of the questions were not so much should a man act in this way but should a human being do so. Why do think that gender is so important? Other than for procreation and health issues it is irreverent.
These questions although gender related  some could be applied to both male and female. I get that this is probably the intended point.

column3: Liberal, Libertarian, Anarchist, Feminist, Egalitarian, Moderate

column73: I found some of the questions were phrased oddly, which made it difficult to make an emphatic decision one way or another. So a lot of my answers came out "neutral".
Some of those questions seem rather leading.

Some questions as written are very much taking a singular view of male sexuality (the penis goes in vagina RAR!) and some lack nuance, but I appreciate the questionnaire. Would you be interested in doing a second stage questionnaire perhaps with more open questions?

column3: Socialist, Feminist, Men's Rights Activist, Egalitarian
column73:
All personal-philosophy must consider the wide social environment in which it is a single piece. You must always ask "what if everyone believed this?" (which is why Ayn Rand is so completely useless).

My central philosophy: "The World Needs All Sorts". Poets, scientists, sewer-cleaners and engineers are all needed. Steven Hawking and Eddie Izzard. You should aim to excel at what you enjoy, but must maintain respect for that which is not you. Never dismiss something out of hand, instead investigate and talk with those who know more than you in that area before making judgement.

The core philosophy that explains why this is important, is from the central realisation of Evolution: "It is not the Strongest species that survives, but the one most Adaptable to change". If as a species we are determined to become Strong at and efficient at our one most powerful current trick (eg: capitalism's drives for efficiency of money-movement), but at the expense of everything else, we lose the ability to react to changing circumstances, and paradoxically we are destined for the scrap-heap! It is only through diversification (of ideas, cultures, and way of doing things) that we can ensure some version of ourselves is suited to whatever the universe throws at us.

tl;dr: Globalism a Shit.
Apart from the single question about the penis, for 'man' read 'person' in all my answers.
all good. John.
Interesting set of questions.

It was unclear if the question was "How desirable are these traits in a man" or "How much do you desire this trait to be integral to being a man" but that might be because I didn't take enough time to read the instructions

To be honest, I don't believe in a non-toxic masculinity - gender roles are toxic, and we should be focussing on abolishing them and allowing people to simply exist, rather than seeking ways to sanitise a structure that systematically oppresses women based on societal norms and perceived biology
Halfway down the voice in my head started reading it all as Jaqen H'ghar from Game of Thrones. This was somewhat amusing.

Examples of the behaviours would be useful as some of them could be interpreted in several ways, making it difficult to give an accurate response without knowing whether the author definition matches the respondent's definition.

This would have given more interesting results if you'd asked a few similar questions replacing man with woman. For the record I would have answered the same way if the questions said woman instead of man but I know others would not.
